President Cyril Ramaphosa addressed the nation on Wednesday, and emphasised the interventions that must continue if  SA is to contain the spread of Covid-19. The address follows a special sitting of the cabinet that considered recommendations of the national coronavirus command council meeting. According to figures released on Wednesday, there were 740,254 confirmed Covid-19 cases across SA and 19,951 fatalities. In his weekly newsletter, Ramaphosa urged South Africans not to be complacent as a second wave of Covid-19 infections would reverse the country's health and economic gains. He extended the national state of disaster and warned South Africans to avoid large gatherings over the festive season. A five-day period of mourning was also announced for those who died from Covid-19. 